==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1753 (in the theological sense); attested in 1830 in the political sense. From {{suffix|absolute|ism|lang=en}} after {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|absolutisme}}.<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.sə.luː.tɪz.m̩/|/ˈæb.sə.ljuː.tɪz.m̩/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.səˌluˌtɪz.m̩/|/ˈæb.səˌljuˌtɪz.m̩/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-absolutism.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|theology}} Doctrine of [[preordination]]; doctrine of absolute decrees; doctrine that God acts in an absolute manner. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>
# {{lb|en|political science}} The principles or practice of absolute or arbitrary government; [[despotism]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|passage=The element of ''absolutism'' and prelacy was controlling.|author=Palfrey}}
# {{lb|en|philosophy}} Belief in a [[metaphysical]] [[absolute]]; belief in [[Absolute]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# [[positiveness|Positiveness]]; the state of being absolute.
# {{lb|en|rare}} The characteristic of being absolute in nature or scope; [[absoluteness]].
#* {{quote-book|year=2003|author=Ruth R. Wisse|title=The Modern Jewish Canon: A Journey Through Language|isbn=0226903184|passage=It was the '''absolutism''' of his ambition to be a perfect writer (and perhaps also the perfect son) that imperiled him.}}

